Code Contexts#

Code in the /packages/syft directory as part of the syft pypi package runs in a variety of places. This is because the same code needed for a user to connect and send messages to a server, is the same code that the server needs to decode those messages and reply or to connect to another server and do the same.

Code in the /packages/grid directory is almost exclusively used to build and run node servers like a domain or network.

Grid Server#

Below is a map of how a single node server, either a domain or a network node can be composed of different containers to achieve different desired configurations.

Note: the small syft icon inside the backend_stream, backend and celeryworker containers.

Entry points are available on the left hand side.

Legend:

  • ⬜️ entry point or container for both domains and networks

  • 🟪 there are a few different storage types depending on Grid versions

  • 🟩 entry point or container optionally available on domains

  • 🟫 entry point or container only available on networks

  • 🟦 entry point or container only available on domains

The simplest thing to interact with is a single domain. You can run a domain on any supported container host such as docker or kubernetes. For development and Desktop deployments we recommend Docker Desktop on macOS, Windows or Linux. If you have Linux desktop or WSL 2 on Windows you can also use docker engine.

Client#

Within syft we have the concept of a client which is an object which knows how to reach a server over a network and contains a copy of a users private key to use when signing messages that it sends.

The important thing to note here is that the domain must be reachable to the client but the client is not able to be reached by the domain, except by replying to an incoming request. This is a common pattern on the web. Web servers usually cannot initiate a connection to your home computers browser out of the blue.

The code running inside the client is on the Users computer, in a python interpreter, most commonly Jupyter Lab (like where we are now).

While the code running inside the Domain, is inside a container running on a container host. In production mode this is usually a Linux server or Kubernetes cluster, but in this case it’s running in development mode on your local machine.

Importing Syft#

First let’s import syft so we can use it to create a client to our domain like the diagram above.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
import syft as sy

Now we can create a client by using the handy login function. The return value of this function is a client object which we will name domain_client.

Creating a Client#

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
domain_client = sy.login(
    port=8081,
    email="info@openmined.org",
    password="changethis"
)

WARNING: CHANGE YOUR USERNAME AND PASSWORD!!! 

Anyone can login as an admin to your node right now because your password is still the default PySyft username and password!!!

Connecting to localhost... done! 	 Logging into test_domain... done!

Note, when we leave the url parameter off, login assumes we mean localhost by default.

Inside the client object you will find a few important things.

The .name attribute shows us the name of the node it is pointing to:

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
domain_client.name

'test_domain'

This client points to a domain called test_domain which matches the name we used during the hagrid launch command above.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
domain_client.address

<Address - Domain:<SpecificLocation:..626a1>>

It has an address which is a UUIDv4, this is randomly generated on creation and is essentially guaranteed to be universially unique.

UUIDs#

Due to the randomness involved in UUIDs, you should expect the ones displayed when you run these cells yourself, to be different from the ones at the time of creating this notebook and taking the screenshots. However the output of your cells should match the logs and database views on your machine.

Read more about UUIDs here:

🔗 Web Link
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universally_unique_identifier
# ⚔️ Runnable Code
domain_client.address.target_id

<SpecificLocation: ced19726404f42449e2ad51826e626a1>

We can see that the domain has a UUID (ced19726404f42449e2ad51826e626a1) which we will see come up later in this session.

And finally the client has at least 1 route to contact it’s server.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
domain_client.routes[0].connection.base_url

<GridURL http://localhost:8081/api/v1>

This matches the fact that we connected to it over port 8081 on the localhost interface which is default when starting a server on a local Desktop setup.

Let’s see where the private key or signing_key which is used to sign all messages is kept. This key is just bytes and we often represent it as hex to make display or storage easier.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
print(type(domain_client.signing_key))
print(bytes(domain_client.signing_key).hex()[0:6], "... hidden")

<class 'nacl.signing.SigningKey'>
2752a3 ... hidden

Since we logged in as the root user (Administrator) using the default credentials, this signing_key is quite powerful, and it’s best not to post these online or print them in your notebooks by accident.

Entry Point#

The first thing to think about is how our messages get routed into the different containers and services. Let’s refer to the diagram above again.

We have a container service called proxy which runs a system called traefik which allows us to define different HTTP routes or paths for our client to access.

The first thing to know is that our Message protocol is based on RPC not REST so most of the application is behind one or two route endpoints, in particular the /api/v1/syft and /api/v1/syft/stream.

We will go into the details about the difference between those two further down.

If you want to learn more about traefik proxy checkout the docs here:

🔗 Web Link
Traefik Proxy

Docker Compose#

To understand how this works lets look at our docker-compose.yml file.

proxy:
  restart: always
  hostname: ${DOMAIN_NAME?Variable not set}
  image: ${DOCKER_IMAGE_TRAEFIK?Variable not set}:${TRAEFIK_VERSION?Variable not set}
  networks:
    - "${TRAEFIK_PUBLIC_NETWORK?Variable not set}"
    - default
  volumes:
    - "./traefik/docker/traefik.yml:/etc/traefik/traefik.yml"
    - "./traefik/docker/dynamic.yml:/etc/traefik/conf/dynamic.yml"
  environment:
    - SERVICE_NAME=proxy
    - RELEASE=${RELEASE:-production}
    - HOSTNAME=${DOMAIN_NAME?Variable not set}
    - HTTP_PORT=${HTTP_PORT}
    - HTTPS_PORT=${HTTPS_PORT}
  ports:
    - "${HTTP_PORT}:81"
  depends_on:
    - "docker-host"

What you can see here is we use a lot of env variables which either come from the default set in our .env file or they are passed in during launch by hagrid.

The defaults for the above variables are likely to be:

DOMAIN_NAME=test_domain
DOCKER_IMAGE_TRAEFIK=traefik
TRAEFIK_VERSION=v2.8.1
RELEASE=development
HOSTNAME=test_domain
HTTP_PORT=8081
HTTPS_PORT=443

We can also see that some configuration is passed into traefik using those volume mounts.

Let’s take a look at how those paths are created for the backend and backend_stream containers.

# /packages/grid/traefik/docker/dynamic.yml
services:
  backend:
    loadBalancer:
      servers:
        - url: "http://proxy:8001"
  backend-stream:
    loadBalancer:
      servers:
        - url: "http://proxy:8011"

routers:
  backend:
    rule: "PathPrefix(`/api`)
    entryPoints:
      - web
      - vpn
    service: "backend"
  backend-stream:
    rule: "PathPrefix(`/api`) && PathPrefix(`/api/v1/syft/stream`)
    entryPoints:
      - web
      - vpn
    service: "backend-stream"

To aid in understanding, unrelated code has been removed from the above file.

You can see here that if you access the main port we are listening on, in this case 8081 that any traffic to /api will go to the backend container, and any traffic to /api/v1/syft/stream will go to the backend_stream container.

You will see that these match up to the diagram above, and show the flow of input into two containers which both have a Node Object inside them, and additionally a copy of the syft python library.

Backend#

Let’s take a look at the backend.dockerfile.

# packages/grid/backend/backend.dockerfile

# copy grid
COPY grid/backend /app/

COPY grid/backend/docker-scripts/start.sh /start.sh
COPY grid/backend/docker-scripts/start-reload.sh /start-reload.sh
COPY grid/backend/worker-start.sh /worker-start.sh
COPY grid/backend/worker-start-reload.sh /worker-start-reload.sh

RUN chmod +x /start.sh
RUN chmod +x /start-reload.sh
RUN chmod +x /worker-start.sh
RUN chmod +x /worker-start-reload.sh

# install syft
RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.cache \
  pip install --user -e /app/syft

# change to worker-start.sh or start-reload.sh as needed
CMD ["bash", "start.sh"]

Here we can see that essentially, the backend container is just a bunch of files from the packages/grid/backend folder and a few startup scripts.

The other main thing to note, other than lots of platform specific dependencies is we install a copy of syft.

If you check the source repo you will see that these backend python files are mostly just Fast API and Celery Worker code to get data into a Node Object where it gets executed by syft.

It turns out we use this same image for 3 different containers:

  • backend

  • backend_stream

  • celeryworker

Let’s take a look at our docker-compose.yml definition.

backend:
  restart: always
  image: "${DOCKER_IMAGE_BACKEND?Variable not set}:${VERSION-latest}"
  depends_on:
    - proxy
    - db
  env_file:
    - .env
  environment:
    - SERVICE_NAME=backend
    - RELEASE=${RELEASE:-production}
    - VERSION=${VERSION}
    - VERSION_HASH=${VERSION_HASH}
    - NODE_TYPE=${NODE_TYPE?Variable not set}
    - DOMAIN_NAME=${DOMAIN_NAME?Variable not set}
    - STACK_API_KEY=${STACK_API_KEY}
    - PORT=8001
    - IGNORE_TLS_ERRORS=${IGNORE_TLS_ERRORS?False}
    - HTTP_PORT=${HTTP_PORT}
    - HTTPS_PORT=${HTTPS_PORT}
    - USE_BLOB_STORAGE=${USE_BLOB_STORAGE}
    - CONTAINER_HOST=${CONTAINER_HOST}
  command: /start.sh
  network_mode: service:proxy

Open the docker-compose.yml file and compare the differences between backend, backend_stream and celeryworker.

The main difference between all three container definitions is just the port they bind to and their startup script. For backend and backend_stream they use docker compose network_mode so, they share a network device; which is why their ports vary. However celeryworker is a consumer so it is not reachable via the network and therefore requires no port. Finally, the entrypoint command is different between the backend containers and celeryworker to execute different code on startup.

The use of network_mode relates to reducing complexity in setting up our bi-directional vpn connections. In Kubernetes we provide iptables rules to route traffic rather than using the same network device.

If you want to learn more about Docker or the docker-compose.yml format and docker compose cli tool, check out the docs:

🔗 Web Link
Docker Documentation
🔗 Web Link
Docker Compose Documentation

Sync vs Async#

The reason we have three containers is to provide two different mechanisms to send in commands to a node. In the next session we will discuss this in more detail but messages which expect an immediate response are considered sync and blocking, examples are login or get.

Examples of async messages are most actions which are sent to the stream endpoint, queued and then consumed by our worker and processed. In this pattern there is no reply to async messages except an acknowledgement (ack) that they were queued. If the result is desired, a later sync message can be used to block and get it.

List Dev Ports#

When running hagrid launch with --dev we enable an extra docker-compose.dev.yml file which also turns on a bunch of handy things like, hot reloading for source code and open ports for things like databases or web admin panels.

We can see what those ports are and even automatically open the right tool by using this shell script. If you are on windows you should be able to run it from WSL 2 or bash if you have it.

🐧🍏 Terminal Command
./scripts/dev_tools.sh

On my machine I get the following output:

test_domain-seaweedfs-1 -> 61940
test_domain-redis-1 -> 61936
test_domain-queue-1 -> 61934
test_domain-db-1 -> 61935

The reason we have random ports is because it can be useful to start multiple nodes on your machine to test things like connecting a domain to a network, in which case we can’t predict exactly which ports will be available.

The dev_tool.sh takes a port as its first argument, and attempts to open that resource in the relevant tool. In the case of db, redis, and mongodb (in 0.8) it will launch TablePlus. If you ask for the ports for seaweedfs or queue (rabbitmq) it will open up your browser with the url for the built in web management UIs.

The default username and password for rabbitmq is guest and guest. It is normal practise to only include these UI’s in development mode which is exactly what the docker-compose.dev.yml does.

We will see these in action below once we look at the different stores.

Logging#

The grid and syft code logs out different things that it does including Exceptions if they happen due to errors or bugs. Checking the logs is a crucial part of the dev experience. Occasionally the logging in ctop has issues with too much output, so sometimes its better to use the builtin docker log command.

Let’s tail the logs for the backend container.

🐧🍏🪟 Terminal Command
docker logs -f test_domain-backend-1

When running docker logs the -f means follow or tail, if we omit this the entire log will just come flying out. This can be handy if we want to see something from earlier, send it to a file with > file.txt or even use grep to search the output for something.

Let’s send a message to the sync endpoint and see if it shows up in the logs.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
domain_client.store

If you have a fresh domain, the store will be empty.

Weird Emojis#

You might notice where it says <UID: ⍰🚃> there are two little emojis. Since syft uses UUIDs everywhere we found printing them and comparing them from line to line quite hard on the eyes, so instead we convert them to emojis. Sometimes there is no emoji in utf-8 at a particular code point so we get a ⍰ instead. This would probably make a nice fun bug fix for anyone interested.

Stream & Worker#

Okay so what about this backend_stream thing and the celeryworker? The stream endpoint and container takes the messages and queues them into our rabbitmq queue where they sit waiting to be consumed by our pool of workers. In this case we have a single worker container test_domain-celeryworker-1, but you can imagine this can be increased to more.

Let’s look at the container map again. Here we can see that messages coming in on the stream endpoint do indeed pass through the backend_stream container and go to the rabbitmq container next, before making their way to the celeryworker container to be processed.

Simply put, the work that an async action takes will be queued and executed on the celeryworker and will not allow CPU intensive work to cause the backend or backend_stream endpoints to slow down enough, that they can’t accept new connections. Additionally in the worst case, if a worker crashes the system can keep queuing new commands and pick up where it left off.

Let’s log the backend_stream and celeryworker containers so we can see this in action.

In two seperate terminal windows run the following commands or use ctop to tail the container logs.

Let’s also open up the rabbitmq interface with the dev_tools.sh.

🐧🍏🪟 Terminal Command
docker logs -f test_domain-backend_stream-1
docker logs -f test_domain-celeryworker-1
./scripts/dev_tools.sh 61934

Okay, now we’re ready to send something async, lets put some data into the system.

First let’s create some super duper secret tensor data with numpy.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
import numpy as np
x = np.array([1, 2, 3])
x

array([1, 2, 3])

Okay, now we can send it into a domain by using the .send() method on the numpy ndarray like so:

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
x_ptr = x.send(domain_client)
x_ptr

<ndarrayPointer -> test_domain:8d3ae9cd5df04c01aa6ba8b38be0d1e4>

The return result is a Pointer with a UUID, we will talk more about this in the next session.

You might have noticed that was a little bit magic 🪄 that the numpy object which knows nothing about syft has a method .send() which interacts with our client. This is one of very few instances where we monkeypatch data types which syft supports to provide a consistent .send() convenience method. We promise no monkeys were harmed in this patching process 🙊.

Now we should see the following on the backend_stream logs:

You can see that it printed Queuing streaming message for processing on worker node.

And in the celeryworker logs:

You can see that it printed Task received and then Task succeeded in 0.029s

If you check rabbitmq you will see some spikes showing messages being published and consumed.

It looks like the message got through, but where did it end up?

Stores#

We have a number of stores in grid for different use cases. All nodes require some kind of store to allow either temporary or persistent storage of objects as they are manipulated in the system.

Redis#

Since every object in syft has a UUID most of our data is stored in what is called a key / value store. Redis is a popular high performance database which allows us to easily store or lookup any object with a particular key, in this case a UUID.

Data you wish to operate on, or the intermediate variables created while using syft usually end up in this key/value store.

If we open the redis view inside TablePlus we can see any data which gets put inside a Node’s .store attribute.

Let’s run the dev_tools.sh with the port for the redis container.

🐧🍏🪟 Terminal Command
./scripts/dev_tools.sh 61936

You can see the UUID (8d3ae9cd5df04c01aa6ba8b38be0d1e4) of the Pointer we got back above matches and on the right we can see the raw bytes mention protobuf and an ndarrayWrapper, that seems to make sense.

If you a running a domain with --use_blob_storage flag (default is True), you will see db15 the 16th key value store in redis is occupied by some additional metadata for our seaweedfs blob storage.

SeaweedFS#

What is the blob storage system you may ask?

BLOB is a backronym which stands for Binary Large Object and is a collection of binary data stored as a single entity. When data is transfered between systems or written to non-volatile memory, it must be serialized into a steam of bytes. Since the largest storage is much bigger than the largest RAM the natural state of most data is serialized as a blob.

In redis there is a limit of 512mb for objects to ensure it can maintain its high performance characteristics.

As you can imagine real world data can often exceed those numbers by several orders of magnitute. Additionally, the way we access the redis store through the backend container, backend_stream container and celeryworker introduces a number of steps which will slow down processing of large amounts of data and require huge jumps in RAM utilization just to shuttle it around.

Instead when dealing with large amounts of data, we prefer to use a seperate system called SeaweedFS which allows high throughput multi-threaded transfers of data between the client and wherever the seaweedfs container is running. There are numerous other cool things SeaweedFS can do which are topics for another time.

🔗 Web Link
SeaweedFS

By utilizing standardized Amazon S3 protocols which SeaweedFS supports, we can obtain a pre-signed url from the backend for both upload and download and then allow the client and blob storage to interact directly.

To make this seamless to the rest of the application, we store a ProxyData object inside the redis store which contains only the meta data needed to retrieve the real object when needed.

Normally this happens automatically for certain types of objects or sizes. One of those types is our built-in Tensor type.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
t = sy.Tensor(x)
t_ptr = t.send(domain_client, tags=["Cool Data"])
t_ptr

Uploading `579ec06ada274a2abfcdb2f66049b737`: 100%|███████████████████| 1/1 [00:00<00:00, 21.61it/s]

<TensorPointer -> test_domain:579ec06ada274a2abfcdb2f66049b737>

Note: We have added a list of tags to apply to this data to make it searchable.

Here we can see that the new TensorPointer has the UUID (579ec06ada274a2abfcdb2f66049b737) and indeed the object inside redis says it contains a ProxyData object.

Now lets fire up the seaweedfs web UI.

🐧🍏🪟 Terminal Command
./scripts/dev_tools.sh 61940

There you can see that the UUID of our object is inside a bucket in SeaweedFS. The bucket UUID comes from a seperate dataset collection object which was created automatically.

PostgreSQL#

Another type of store we have in grid is our metadata store. This is where we keep data which isn’t the actual private data or variables during computation, but rather is related to the operations of the grid node, its users and their RBAC (Role-based access control) permissions.

Let’s open the postgresql database which is in the container called db and take a look.

🐧🍏 Terminal Command
./scripts/dev_tools.sh 61935

You should see a TablePlus window pop up, already connected. On the left you can see some of the tables in our database.

Since private data doesn’t lend itself very well to traditional SQL style where queries we don’t use any complex SQL in syft. However if you are interested in learning the basics of SQL, there is a great interactive tutorial called SQLBolt.

🔗 Web Link
https://sqlbolt.com/

To see where the schema is defined, checkout the packages/grid/backend/alembic/versions folder.

You can read more about Alembic on its website.

Alembic

Network#

Now that we understand how a client communicates with a single domain let’s go a step further and discuss network servers and how they fit into the picture.

Looking back at our container map we can see that there are some routes and containers which are for domains or networks only.

The easiest way to think about the difference is that a domain holds private data.
If we look at the definition of the word domain it is:

domain
/də(ʊ)ˈmeɪn/
an area of territory owned or controlled by a particular ruler or government.

Where as a network connects domains and their users together.

Naturally this means a network does not need seaweedfs blob storage, or a frontend, while a domain does not require the ability to handle VPN key management.

However under the hood they run much of the same containers and code, and different variations and configurations of a node will likely be created in the future.

Note to run both of these nodes at the same time requires additional CPU and RAM.

Joining a Network#

Now that our network is running we can tell our domain to join it.

To do so we need to make our domain aware of the network and we do that by running a command between the two clients.

First we need a client for the network:

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
network_client = sy.login(port=8082)

Connecting to localhost... done! 	 Logging into test_network... as GUEST...done!

This can be done without any credentials as we are only a guest not the root user.

If we have a root user client to our domain, this will signify we are the owner of the domain and that we have the permission to tell it to do things like connect to a network node. We can then tell our domain to exchange its verify_key with the network.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
response = domain_client.networking.initiate_exchange_credentials(
    client=network_client
)

If we run the dev_tools.sh script again we can find the port for test_network-db-1 and open it up in TablePlus.
For me its port 56970:

🐧🍏🪟 Terminal Command
./scripts/dev_tools.sh 56970

If we check the node table we will see that we have a new entry which contains the name and UUID (ced19726404f42449e2ad51826e626a1) of the domain node we just registered as well as a verify_key.

This verify_key or public key allows us to verify every time a domain contacts us and tells us it wants to modify something about its networking, that the message came from the legitimate domain or root user (Administrator) and that we should trust it.

The next step we need to do to give a network knowledge of our domain is to tell it how we can be contacted. This is important as this allows a network to pass this connection information on to other users or domains in future when trying to locate our domain.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
response = domain_client.networking.add_route_for(
    client=network_client,
    source_node_url="http://localhost:8081",
    autodetect=False
)

Looking in our network database we can now see that there is a route for our domain on localhost:8081 of course this will only work in our local development setup, if this was a real live domain that url would usually be a publicly addressable ip or hostname and port.

Search#

Okay, now that we have registered our domain and added a route what can we do? One of the purposes of registering a domain with a network is to provide data search and discovery.

By using a client to a network, we can search to see if there is any Cool Data out there.

network_client.search(["Cool Data"])
id name host_or_ip is_vpn private protocol port
0 ced19726404f42449e2ad51826e626a1 test_domain localhost False False http 8081

We should see that our Tensor which was tagged Cool Data is showing up. Knowing this information we can get a client to the listed domain above and obtain a pointer to that data item.

Proxy Client#

Let’s ask the network to give a list of all it’s linked domains.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
network_client.domains
host_or_ip id is_vpn name port private protocol
0 localhost ced19726404f42449e2ad51826e626a1 0 test_domain 8081 0 http

Here we can see a list of domains that are available on this network and if that host_or_ip and port were available publicly we could connect to it directly.

Alternatively we can ask the network to proxy our commands via its own private connection to this domain.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
proxy_client = network_client.domains["ced19726404f42449e2ad51826e626a1"]

We now have a guest client to our domain via the network node, if you send messages you can verify in the network logs that they pass through the network node.

Let’s check the domain store using our new proxy client.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
proxy_client.store

We can also see our Cool Data is available.

Getting Data#

Now that we have a pointer to that data, let’s try to get it.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
try:
    cool_ptr.get(delete_obj=False)
except Exception:
    print("You do not have permission to .get() Object on the node. Please submit a request.")

[2022-10-05T13:49:49.482955+1000][CRITICAL][logger]][1168] Address unknown - cannot forward message. Throwing it away.

You do not have permission to .get() Object on the node. Please submit a request.

This should fail because you do not have permission, however with an authorized client like the root user (Administrator) one we used earlier things will be different.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
cool_ptr = domain_client.store["579ec06ada274a2abfcdb2f66049b737"]
cool_data = cool_ptr.get(delete_obj=False)
cool_data

Tensor(child=[1 2 3])

It’s important to understand this principal. Data by default is not readable (copyable) by others. However computation that uses private data can be constructed within certain limits and the results of that computation can be obtained safely. We will go into detail about this in a later session.

Tailscale#

Okay so what if the domain is in a restricted network and doesn’t want to provide a public address, or the owner of the domain can’t open ports on their internet connections firewall?

That’s where the use of our end-to-end encrypted VPN comes into play. We utilize a very popular zero-configuration VPN tool called tailscale. Tailscale is built on the open source wireguard protocol and provides free open source clients. Normally you pay tailscale for key sharing to allow your devices to trust each other, but there is an open source project called headscale which provides this functionality for free.

🔗 Web Link
Tailscale

To understand how tailscale (and other systems) bypasses Firewalls and NATs they have written an excellent blog post explaining the process indepth.

📘 Blog Post
How NAT traversal works

Okay so where is this tailscale code?

# packages/grid/docker-compose.yml
tailscale:
    profiles:
      - vpn
    image: "${DOCKER_IMAGE_TAILSCALE?Variable not set}:${VERSION-latest}"
    environment:
      - SERVICE_NAME=tailscale
      - RELEASE=${RELEASE:-production}
      - HOSTNAME=${DOMAIN_NAME?Variable not set}
      - STACK_API_KEY=$STACK_API_KEY
    volumes:
      - tailscale-data:/var/lib/tailscale
      - "/dev/net/tun:/dev/net/tun" # Required for tailscale to work
    cap_add: # Required for tailscale to work
      - net_admin
      - sys_module
    depends_on:
      - proxy
    network_mode: service:proxy

Here we can see that we are building and running a container for the tailscale VPN. This provides us with the tailscale client binary as well as the correct permissions to modify the hosts network to add the IP address to its network interface.

# packages/grid/vpn.tailscale.dockerfile
FROM tailscale/tailscale:v1.22.0

RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.cache \
    pip install --user -r requirements.txt

COPY ./tailscale.sh /tailscale/tailscale.sh
COPY ./tailscale.py /tailscale/tailscale.py

CMD ["sh", "-c", "/tailscale/tailscale.sh ${HOSTNAME}"]

The docker image just takes the existing official tailscale image and adds a custom entrypoint script and python script on top.

Inside those files you will find that we run a small internal python API which responds to HTTP commands to trigger actions inside the container.

This allows us to run tailscale commands like tailscale up to connect to a particular key server such as headscale.

Docker network_mode#

As mentioned earlier a handful of our containers use the same network_mode which is docker parlance for using the same network device. This means that the tailscale container also shares that device and can add the VPN ip and routes to it.

Since we are listening on port 80 internally for the traefik proxy, this means traffic over the VPN IP will also be routed through traefik the same way as if it came from the outside.

Additionally when a container like backend or celeryworker wants to contact another host over the VPN the ip route is available to the containers network stack already.

As mentioned earlier, on kubernetes we do something a bit more advanced which we will explain in a later session.

Headscale#

Tailscale requires that a client connect to a server which shares the public keys for all the other clients as well as information on how to reach them (including helping bypass firewalls and NATs to establish peer-to-peer connections).

The headscale container image does something similar to the tailscale one above where we take the official image and overlay the same python API to allow our backend application containers to issue commands to do things like create VPN keys for clients to use when connecting.

To be able to reach the headscale key server the tailscale clients need a route which is why the network nodes also have a /vpn route which passes traffic through to the headscale service.

🔗 Web Link
Headscale

VPN#

Okay, lets try connecting our domain to our network over this tailscale VPN.

# ⚔️ Runnable Code
domain_client.apply_to_network(network_client)

1/3 Joining Network
2/3 Secure VPN Connected
3/3 Network Registration Complete

There are quite a lot of steps happening in this process, as the domain is contacting the network asking for a key and then contacting headscale and asking it how to connect to the VPN.

Internally, the network is also running a tailscale container so that it also has an IP address on the same VPN network.

Firstly we can see a new route has been added to the network database for our domain and this time it’s an IP. The ip address is from a private range that is set in the headscale configuration which starts with 100.64.0.1 and goes upwards.

This CIDR block is seperate from the public internet and has millions of IPs so we shouldn’t worry about running out. Additionally, headscale will never recycle these IPs so within a specific network these IPs should be unique.

You can read more about CIDR here:

🔗 Web Link
Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR)

The next thing we can do is verify this is working as we expect by jumping into our tailscale container with ctop.

🐧🍏🪟 Terminal Command
ctop

Find either of the tailscale containers and press enter then choose [e] exec shell (or just press e in future).

Here we can run a few commands to see what is happening:

🐧🍏🪟 Terminal Command
tailscale status
wget 100.64.0.1/api/v1/syft
tailscale debug prefs

Firstly, tailscale status shows we are connected, have an IP address assigned and that the connection is a relay via a server. This is because the two docker compose stacks are isolated from each other and therefore are unable to connect peer-to-peer (p2p) so they are routing their traffic via one of tailscale’s DERP servers. Of course this is still safe because the traffic is end-to-end (e2e) encrypted.

We can open up this connection so its p2p, or run our own DERP servers if we wish.

To read more about DERP servers and running custom ones see here:

🔗 Web Link
Custom DERP Servers

The other thing we can see in the debug info is that the original connection is established through docker-host:8082 this is just a little work around we use in docker local development mode to allow isolated stacks to communicate with each other through the port we bind to the main localhost interface on the higher up docker host. This also explains the presence of a little container called docker-host in the docker-compose.yml file.

Network Diagram#

It’s worth taking a moment to step back and look at some of the things we have just implemented. When accessing your local Desktop domain you can connect directly via localhost just like Data Scientist 3 to Domain 2 in the above diagram.

Your Desktop machine is likely behind a firewall and cannot be connected to directly by other domains or networks and their Data Scientists without either placing it on the open internet, such as Domain 2 or Solitary Domain 3; or by joining a network like Network A and adding the tailscale VPN.

Once the VPN is connected, domains such as Domain 1 and Domain 2 can communicate directly, even with a firewall, and external parties such as Data Scientist 1 can connect to Domain 2 via a ProxyClient through Network A.

TLS#

The networking component would not be complete without mentioning our TLS support. Most of the time we have discussed ports and protocols in terms of 80** or HTTP and most of the time during developement we run everything without TLS the encryption layer that is used in our web browsers when we type https://.

One of the reasons why TLS is complicated to run in development mode is because the so called TLS or SSL certificates that provide the padlock, are only valid for real domains.

This means things like localhost or 100.64.0.1 are not valid for TLS certificates and setting up fake domain names and DNS is also complicated for development mode.

To help with testing this we use some tools to generate fake (so called self-signed) TLS certificates to use in testing and then tell our stack and python clients to ignore TLS errors and trust these special certificates.

If you wish to know more about how this works, take a look at the stack.test.integration.tls tests, and the docker-compose.test.yml and docker-compose.tls.yml files which modify the system to require TLS certificates, generate and mount these certs and provide URL rewriting inside traefik to allow port 443 or other ports to carry TLS traffic.

It is worth noting that we do not run HTTPS over the VPN because doing so would require self-signed certificates but provide little benefit since the tailscale traffic is already e2e encrypted.
